<br>
One thing I was thinking about was the possibility of organising regular Guild Quests as a way of attracting new members. Assuming that we want to actively seek new members - we might NOT...<br>
<br>
I was thinking that if we wanted (for example) some Druid members, we could organise a quest (or reward) appropriate for that class... and offer guild membership as part of the prize...<br>
<br>
This makes the Quest less of a &quot;lottery&quot; for current members and more of a way of attracting new members - which as I said we might NOT want to do...!?<br>
<br>
An alternative that I thought of, was the possibility of organising a *regular* quest (open to anyone - or open to guild members?). Regular in terms of timing, but the actual quest could change. For example to celebrate the start of *each* New Year IN NORRATH... we would hold a quest - with the quest ending at the end of NORRATH's January. Each &quot;year&quot; the quest would be different, but could be announced at the same place (for example Freeport) - or each of the members could announce the quest in whatever zone they are in - but the quest &quot;target item&quot; would have to be taken to (for example) Freeport.<br>
<br>
I *think* a year in NORRATH is less than a month real time, so maybe that's too many quests...<br>
<br>
What d'ya think?<br>
<br>
cheers<br>
Wegian<br>
